snippet: For the first time since World War II, Americans choose a president who pledged to reverse the internationalism practiced by both parties....
abstract: News Analysis; Donald Trump's win in 2016 presidential election upends both international order and raises questions about America's place in world, foreshadowing a country largely focused on its own affairs; outcome adds to growing nativist, nationalist, closed-border movements around world and hints at future global conflicts to come.

byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Jaime Yaya Barry and Dionne Searcey from Dakar, Senegal; Stephen Castle from London; Melissa Eddy from Berlin; Jeffrey Gettleman from Nairobi; Yufan Huang from Beijing; Ivan Nechepurenko from Moscow; Motoko Rich from Tokyo; and Elisabeth Malkin, Kirk Semple and Paulina Villegas from Mexico City.

lead_paragraph: For the first time since World War II, Americans choose a president who pledged to reverse the internationalism practiced by both parties.

headline.print_headline: Around the World, Uncertainty and Fear That ‘All Bets Are Off’
headline.main: Donald Trump’s Victory Promises to Upend the International Order
